{"title_page": "Lesley Manyathela Golden Boot", "text_new": "{{Infobox award\n| name = Lesley Manyathela Golden Boot\n| subheader = <!-- or | current_awards = -->\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| description = The leading goalscorer in a given Premier Division season.\n| sponsor = \n| country = South Africa\n| presenter = [[Premier Soccer League]]\n| former name = \n| year = 1997\n| year2 = 2019\n| holder = [[Mwape Musonda]] <!-- or | winner = or | winners = -->\n| most_wins = [[Collins Mbesuma]] (2)\n}}\n\n'''The Lesley Manyathela Golden Boot''' is an annual [[association football]] award presented by the [[Premier Soccer League]] to the leading goalscorer in the [[South African Premier Division]].<ref>{{cite web|title=NSL Constitution|url=http://images.supersport.com/NSL%20Constitution%20as%20amended%2013%20November%202010.pdf|publisher=Premier Soccer League|format=pdf|accessdate=13 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304041154/http://images.supersport.com/NSL%20Constitution%20as%20amended%2013%20November%202010.pdf|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The award, colloquially known as the golden boot or PSL Golden Boot, has been presented since the inception of the post-[[apartheid]] format of the league in 1996. It was named in 2003 in honour of [[Lesley Manyathela]], a [[South Africa national football team|South African international]] footballer and former recipient of the award who died in a motor vehicle collision in August of that year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/Safa-retires-Lesleys-jersey-20030814|title=Safa retires Lesley's jersey|publisher=News 24|date=15 August 2003|accessdate=17 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517153450/https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/Safa-retires-Lesleys-jersey-20030814|archive-date=2018-05-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Wilfred Mugeyi]] was the first recipient of the award after he scored 22 goals for [[Bush Bucks F.C.|Bush Bucks]] in the [[1996\u201397 Premier Soccer League|inaugural Premier Division season]].<ref name=hist>{{cite news|url=http://vodacomsoccer.co.za/news/general/168/throwback-thursday:-golden-boot-winners-of-yesteryear|title=Throwback Thursday: Golden Boot winners of yesteryear|publisher=Vodacom Soccer|accessdate=6 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906163239/http://vodacomsoccer.co.za/news/general/168/throwback-thursday:-golden-boot-winners-of-yesteryear|archive-date=2018-09-06|url-status=live}}</ref> He is one of only four players to have scored 20 or more goals in a season alongside [[Pollen Ndlanya]], [[Collins Mbesuma]] and [[Siyabonga Nomvethe]].<ref name=hist/> Mbesuma holds the record for the most goals scored in a single campaign following his return of 25 goals for [[Kaizer Chiefs]] in the [[Premier Soccer League 2004-05|2004\u201305 season]].<ref name=CM>{{cite news|url=https://www.soccerladuma.co.za/news/get-published-show/who-will-break-mbesumas-record-25-goals/229363|title=Can Anyone Break Mbesuma's Record?|publisher=Soccer Laduma|date=19 April 2016|accessdate=14 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180515043550/https://www.soccerladuma.co.za/news/get-published-show/who-will-break-mbesumas-record-25-goals/229363|archive-date=2018-05-15|url-status=dead}}</ref> He is also the only player to have won the award more than once, having claimed the trophy for a second time during his spell with [[Mpumalanga Black Aces F.C.|Mpumalanga Black Aces]] in 2016.<ref name=CM/> \n\n[[Bernard Parker]] holds the record for the fewest goals needed to win the award, with his return of 10 goals for Kaizer Chiefs in the [[Premier Soccer League 2013-14|2013\u201314 season]] earning him the accolade.<ref name=TGS>{{cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/sport/soccer/psl/sundowns-tau-polokwanes-ramagalela-in-two-way-race-for-golden-boot-14718532|title=Sundowns' Tau, Polokwane's Ramagalela in two-way race for Golden Boot|publisher=Independent Online|date=30 April 2018|accessdate=5 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905175929/https://www.iol.co.za/sport/soccer/psl/sundowns-tau-polokwanes-ramagalela-in-two-way-race-for-golden-boot-14718532|archive-date=2018-09-05|url-status=live}}</ref> The award has only been shared once in the Premier Division's history, an occurrence which took place after the [[2017\u201318 South African Premier Division|2017\u201318 season]] after [[Rodney Ramagalela]] of [[Polokwane City F.C.|Polokwane City]] and [[Percy Tau]] of [[Mamelodi Sundowns F.C.|Mamelodi Sundowns]] both ended the campaign on 11 goals.<ref name=TGS/> Players from [[Moroka Swallows F.C.|Moroka Swallows]] and Kaizer Chiefs have won the award the most times, with each club having four unique winners.<ref name=hist/> The award has been won on fourteen occasions by South African nationals, the most by any nation.\n\n==Winners==\n[[File:Bernard Parker FC Twente.jpg|thumb|right|[[Bernard Parker]] (pictured here during his time with Dutch side [[FC Twente|Twente]]) holds the record for the fewest goals needed to win the award. His tally of 10 goals for [[Kaizer Chiefs]] earned him the Golden Boot in 2014.|alt=Bernard Parker holds the record for the lowest number of goals needed to win the award.]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|+Key\n!scope=\"row\"|'''Player {{small|(X)}}\n|Name of the player and number of times they had won the award at that point (if more than one)\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center; background:#B0C4DE\"|{{dagger}}\n|Indicates multiple award winners in the same season\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center; background:#FFE6BD\"|{{double-dagger}}\n|Denotes the club were [[South African Premier Division]] champions in the same season\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|+Lesley Manyathela Golden Boot winners\n!scope=\"col\"|Season\n!scope=\"col\"|Player\n!scope=\"col\"|Nationality\n!scope=\"col\"|Club\n!scope=\"col