a wins PSL's Golden Boot|publisher=Kick Off|date=27 May 2017|accessdate=14 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180514213456/http://www.kickoff.com/news/75662/cape-town-citys-lebogang-manyama-wins-psls-golden-boot|archive-date=2018-05-14|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"#B0C4DE\"|[[2017\u201318 South African Premier Division|2017\u201318]]{{sup|{{dagger}}}}\n!scope=\"row\"|{{sortname|Rodney|Ramagalela}}\n|{{flag|South Africa}}\n|[[Polokwane City F.C.|Polokwane City]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|11\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|<ref name=share>{{cite news|url=https://m.sport24.co.za/Soccer/PSL/tau-kekana-nominated-for-psl-footballer-of-the-season-20180521|title=Sundowns dominate PSL Award nominations|publisher=News 24|date=21 May 2018|accessdate=23 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523173134/https://m.sport24.co.za/Soccer/PSL/tau-kekana-nominated-for-psl-footballer-of-the-season-20180521|archive-date=2018-05-23|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"#B0C4DE\"|[[2017\u201318 South African Premier Division|2017\u201318]]{{sup|{{dagger}}}}\n!scope=\"row\"|{{sortname|Percy|Tau}}\n|{{flag|South Africa}}\n|scope=\"row\" style=\"background:#FFE6BD\"|[[Mamelodi Sundowns F.C.|Mamelodi Sundowns]]{{sup|{{double-dagger}}}}\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|11\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|<ref name=share/>\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 South African Premier Division|2018\u201319]]\n!scope=\"row\"|{{sortname|Mwape|Musonda}}\n|{{flag|Zambia}}\n|[[Black Leopards F.C.|Black Leopards]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|16\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/psl-top-goal-scorers-for-2018-19-season/|title=PSL: Top goal scorers for 2018/19 season|publisher=The South African|last=Breakfast|first=Siviwe|date=11 May 2019|accessdate=11 May 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Awards won by nationality==\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Country\n!scope=\"col\"|Total\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{flagcountry|South Africa}}\n|align=\"center\"|{{nts|14}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{flagcountry|Zambia}}\n|align=\"center\"|{{nts|6}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{flagcountry|Zimbabwe}}\n|align=\"center\"|{{nts|3}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{flagcountry|Senegal}}\n|align=\"center\"|{{nts|1}}\n|}\n\n==Awards by club==\n\n[[File:Mame Niang.jpg|thumb|[[Mame Niang]] (pictured here during his time with Norwegian side [[Viking FK|Viking]]) is one of four [[Moroka Swallows F.C.|Moroka Swallows]] players to have won the Golden Boot award.]]\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Club\n!scope=\"col\"|Total\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Moroka Swallows F.C.|Moroka Swallows]]\n| align=\"center\" |{{nts|4}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Kaizer Chiefs F.C.|Kaizer Chiefs]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{nts|4}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Manning Rangers F.C.|Manning Rangers]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{nts|3}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Mamelodi Sundowns F.C.|Mamelodi Sundowns]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{nts|2}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Orlando Pirates]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{nts|2}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Bush Bucks F.C.|Bush Bucks]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{nts|1}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Cape Town City F.C. (2016)|Cape Town City]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{nts|1}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Free State Stars F.C.|Free State Stars]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{nts|1}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Lamontville Golden Arrows F.C.|Golden Arrows]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{nts|1}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Jomo Cosmos F.C.|Jomo Cosmos]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{nts|1}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Mpumalanga Black Aces F.C.|Mpumalanga Black Aces]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{nts|1}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Polokwane City F.C.|Polokwane City]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{nts|1}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[AmaZulu F.C.|Zulu Royals]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{nts|1}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Black Leopards F.C.|Black Leopards]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{nts|1}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Premier Soccer League awards}}\n{{Portal bar|Association football|Football in Africa}}\n\n{{featured list}}\n[[Category:Premier Soccer League]]\n[[Category:African football trophies and awards]]\n[[Category:Soccer in South Africa]]\n", "name_user": "Liam E. Bekker", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lesley_Manyathela_Golden_Boot"}
{"title_page": "William Robert Hay", "text_new": "{{under construction}}\n[[File:William Robert Hay Reynolds.png|thumb|William Robert Hay, 1837 engraving]]\n'''William Robert Hay''' (1761\u20131839) was a British barrister, cleric and magistrate, one of the Manchester group associated with the [[Peterloo Massacre]].\n\n==Early life==\nHe was the son of Edward Hay, a diplomat and [[Governor of Barbados]], and his wife Mary Flower, and grandson of [[George Hay, 8th Earl of Kinnoull]]. Born in Portugal, he was sent when young to England, and was brought up for some years by Archbishop [[Robert Hay Drummond]], his uncle. He was on good terms with [[Robert Hay-Drummond, 10th Earl of Kinnoull|Robert]], the archbishop's eldest son, and was sent to [[Westminster School]] with his older brother Thomas.<ref name=\"Raines\">{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry Hoyle |title=The vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |pages=284-285 |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n94/mode/2up}}</ref> He matriculated at [[Christ Church, Oxford]] in December 1776, six months after Thomas and at age 15, graduating B.A. 1780 and M.A. in 1783.<ref>{{alox2|title=Hay, William Robert}}</ref><ref>{{alox2|title=Hay, Thomas (2)}}</ref>\n\nHay entered the [[Inner Temple]] in 1781, and was [[called to the bar]] in 1788. He then went the [[northern circuit]]. He had little success as a barrister, but was employed by [[Sir John Parker Mosley, 1st Baronet]] as steward to the Manchester manorial court.<ref name=\"Raines\"/> \n\n==Clerical career==\nPossibly influenced by [[Lewis Bagot]], a connection by marriage, Hay was ordained deacon in 1797, priest in 1798, and was placed at [[Ashton-under-Lyne]].<ref name=\"Raines2\">{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry Hoyle |title=The Vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |page=286 |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n96/mode/2up}}</ref> He was assistant curate at [[Disley]], in 1798.<ref name=\"CCEd\">{{CCEd |type=person |id=86938 |name=Hay, William Robert |year1=1798 |year2=1820 |accessed=1 April 2020 }}</ref> In 1799 he was curate at [[Hollinwood, Greater Manchester|Hollinwood]] for Rev. John Darbey.<ref name=\"CCEd\"/> He lived at [[Dukenfield Lodge]], a property in his wife's family that was owned by Francis Dukinfield Astley.<ref name=\"Raines2\"/><ref>{{cite book |title=The County Palatine Of Chester: 2,2 |date=1810 |publisher=T. Cadell And W. Davies |page=784 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4T9aAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA784 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1802 [[Charles Bragge]], a family connection, presented Hay to the rectory of [[Ackworth]] in Yorkshire.<ref name=\"Raines3\">{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry Hoyle |title=The Vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |page=287 |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n97/mode/2up}}</ref> In 1806 [[William Markham (bishop)|William Markham]] gave him a prebend in [[York Minster]].<ref name=\"Raines3\"/>\n\n==Magistrate==\nIn 1803 Hay was elected chairman of the quarter sessions for [[Salford Hundred]], succeeding [[Thomas Butterworth Bayley]], who had died in 1802; at this point he had been a [[justice of the peace]] in the [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], [[Lancashire]] and [[Cheshire]] for some years. He held this position to 1823. Salford Hundred, one of the four traditional divisions of Lancashire, was centered on Manchester.<ref name=\"Raines3\"/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Navickas |first1=Katrina |title=Loyalism and Radicalism in Lancashire, 1798-1815 |date=2009 |publisher=OUP Oxford |isbn=978-0-19-955967-1 |page=120 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0xYUDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA120 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Taylor |first1=Peter |title=Quarter sessions in Lancashire in the middle of the eighteenth century: the court in session and its records |journal=Journal of the Historic Society of Lancashire and Cheshire. |date=1989 |volume=139 |url=https://www.hslc.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/139-4-Taylor.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Bayley, Thomas Butterworth|volume=3}}</ref><ref name=\"GM\">{{cite book |title=The Gentleman's Magazine |date=1840 |publisher=W. Pickering |pages=95-96 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=TCVIAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA95 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn January 1819, Hay was called out in the series \"Letters to the Treason-Hunting Municipality of Manchester\" appearing in the ''[[Manchester Observer]]'', by the radical printer William Ogden: \"As a magistrate, you have taken an active part in committing to prison a great number of not only ''innocent'' but ''worthy'' men\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Poole |first1=Robert |title=Peterloo: The English Uprising |date=2019 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-108620-5 |page=22 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=rdShDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA202 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Chetham Society |first1=Manchester |title=Remains, historical and literary, connected with the palatine counties of Lancaster and Chester. New ser |date=1883 |publisher=Manchester |page=288 |url=https://archive.org/details/remainshistornew02chetuoft/page/288/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\nPresent as a magistrate on 16 August 1819 at [[Peterloo]], Hay wrote the letter of that evening to [[Lord Sidmouth]] giving an account of the events, [[James Norris (lawyer)|James Norris]] being \"very much fatigued by the harrassing duty of this day\". He included the reading of the [[Riot Act]], and the arrests of [[Henry Hunt (politician)|Henry Hunt]] and [[Joseph Johnson]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry Hoyle |title=The Vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |page=291 |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n102/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1819, Hay attended a dinner given by [[Lord Liverpool]], the Prime Minister, where he was treated with high regard by [[Sir John Copley]], the [[Solicitor General for England and Wales|Solicitor General]]. The [[Seditious Meetings Act 1819]] of December reportedly owes clauses to suggestions made by Hay to Copley.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry Hoyle |title=The Vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |page=294 note |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n104/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nHay was created vicar of [[Rochdale]] on 3 January 1820.<ref name=\"CCEd\"/> The incumbent Thomas Drake (1745\u20131819) had died in September.<ref>{{acad|id=DRK764T|name=Drake, Thomas}}</ref> Other candidates for this wealthy living were [[Thomas Dunham Whitaker]], and [[George D'Oyly]] who had better prospects elsewhere at [[Lambeth]]. Hay was successful with the backing of the Manchester municipal establishment. He was seriously ill in 1824.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry H. (Henry Hoyle) |title=The Vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |pages=295-296 |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n106/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\nHay died on 10 December 1839, at Ackworth rectory. His obituary in the ''[[Gentleman's Magazine]]'' compared Hay's role at Peterloo with that of [[Thomas Phillips (mayor)|Sir Thomas Phillips]] in the recent [[Newport Rising]].<ref name=\"GM\"/>\n\n==Family==\nHay married in 1793 Mary Wagstaffe, widow of [[John Astley (painter)|John Astley]], daughter of William Wagstaffe.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lodge |first1=Edmund |title=The Peerage of the British Empire, as at Present Existing, Arranged and Printed from the Personal Communications of the Nobility |date=1832 |publisher=Saunders and Otley |page=237 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=IIsUAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA237 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hay, William Robert}}\n[[Category:1761 births]]\n[[Category:1839 deaths]]\n[[Category:British Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:British barristers]]\n[[Category:Magistrates]]\n", "text_old": "{{under construction}}\n[[File:William Robert Hay Reynolds.png|thumb|William Robert Hay, 1837 engraving]]\n'''William Robert Hay''' (1761\u20131839) was a British barrister, cleric and magistrate, one of the Manchester group associated with the [[Peterloo Massacre]].\n\n==Early life==\nHe was the son of Edward Hay, a diplomat and [[Governor of Barbados]], and his wife Mary Flower, and grandson of [[George Hay, 8th Earl of Kinnoull]]. Born in Portugal, he was sent when young to England, and was brought up for some years by Archbishop [[Robert Hay Drummond]], his uncle. He was on good terms with [[Robert Hay-Drummond, 10th Earl of Kinnoull|Robert]], the archbishop's eldest son, and was sent to [[Westminster School]] with his older brother Thomas.<ref name=\"Raines\">{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry Hoyle |title=The vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |pages=284-285 |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n94/mode/2up}}</ref> He matriculated at [[Christ Church, Oxford]] in December 1776, six months after Thomas and at age 15, graduating B.A. 1780 and M.A. in 1783.<ref>{{alox2|title=Hay, William Robert}}</ref><ref>{{alox2|title=Hay, Thomas (2)}}</ref>\n\nHay entered the [[Inner Temple]] in 1781, and was [[called to the bar]] in 1788. He then went the [[northern circuit]]. He had little success as a barrister, but was employed by [[Sir John Parker Mosley, 1st Baronet]] as steward to the Manchester manorial court.<ref name=\"Raines\"/> \n\n==Clerical career==\nPossibly influenced by [[Lewis Bagot]], a connection by marriage, Hay was ordained deacon in 1797, priest in 1798, and was placed at [[Ashton-under-Lyne]].<ref name=\"Raines2\">{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry Hoyle |title=The Vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |page=286 |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n96/mode/2up}}</ref> He was assistant curate at [[Disley]], in 1798.<ref name=\"CCEd\">{{CCEd |type=person |id=86938 |name=Hay, William Robert |year1=1798 |year2=1820 |accessed=1 April 2020 }}</ref> In 1799 he was curate at [[Hollinwood, Greater Manchester|Hollinwood]] for Rev. John Darbey.<ref name=\"CCEd\"/> He lived at [[Dukenfield Lodge]], a property in his wife's family that was owned by Francis Dukinfield Astley.<ref name=\"Raines2\"/><ref>{{cite book |title=The County Palatine Of Chester: 2,2 |date=1810 |publisher=T. Cadell And W. Davies |page=784 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4T9aAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA784 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1802 [[Charles Bragge]], a family connection, presented Hay to the rectory of [[Ackworth]] in Yorkshire.<ref name=\"Raines3\">{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry Hoyle |title=The Vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |page=287 |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n97/mode/2up}}</ref> In 1806 [[William Markham (bishop)|William Markham]] gave him a prebend in [[York Minster]].<ref name=\"Raines3\"/>\n\n==Magistrate==\nIn 1803 Hay was elected chairman of the quarter sessions for [[Salford Hundred]], succeeding [[Thomas Butterworth Bayley]], who had died in 1802; at this point he had been a [[justice of the peace]] in the [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], [[Lancashire]] and [[Cheshire]] for some years. He held this position to 1823. Salford Hundred, one of the four traditional divisions of Lancashire, was centered on Manchester.<ref name=\"Raines3\"/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Navickas |first1=Katrina |title=Loyalism and Radicalism in Lancashire, 1798-1815 |date=2009 |publisher=OUP Oxford |isbn=978-0-19-955967-1 |page=120 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0xYUDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA120 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Taylor |first1=Peter |title=Quarter sessions in Lancashire in the middle of the eighteenth century: the court in session and its records |journal=Journal of the Historic Society of Lancashire and Cheshire. |date=1989 |volume=139 |url=https://www.hslc.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/139-4-Taylor.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Bayley, Thomas Butterworth|volume=3}}</ref><ref name=\"GM\">{{cite book |title=The Gentleman's Magazine |date=1840 |publisher=W. Pickering |pages=95-96 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=TCVIAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA95 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn January 1819, Hay was called out in the series \"Letters to the Treason-Hunting Municipality of Manchester\" appearing in the ''[[Manchester Observer]]'', by the radical printer William Ogden: \"As a magistrate, you have taken an active part in committing to prison a great number of not only ''innocent'' but ''worthy'' men\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Poole |first1=Robert |title=Peterloo: The English Uprising |date=2019 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-108620-5 |page=22 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=rdShDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA202 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Chetham Society |first1=Manchester |title=Remains, historical and literary, connected with the palatine counties of Lancaster and Chester. New ser |date=1883 |publisher=Manchester |page=288 |url=https://archive.org/details/remainshistornew02chetuoft/page/288/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\nPresent as a magistrate on 16 August 1819 at [[Peterloo]], Hay wrote the letter of that evening to [[Lord Sidmouth]] giving an account of the events, [[James Norris (lawyer)|James Norris]] being \"very much fatigued by the harrassing duty of this day\". He included the reading of the [[Riot Act]], and the arrests of [[Henry Hunt (politician)|Henry Hunt]] and [[Joseph Johnson]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry Hoyle |title=The Vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |page=291 |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n102/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1819, Hay attended a dinner given by [[Lord Liverpool]], the Prime Minister, where he was treated with high regard by [[Sir John Copley]], the [[Solicitor General for England and Wales|Solicitor General]]. The [[Seditious Meetings Act 1819]] of December reportedly owes clauses to suggestions made by Hay to Copley.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry Hoyle |title=The Vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |page=294 note |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n104/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nHay was created vicar of [[Rochdale]] on 3 January 1820.<ref name=\"CCEd\"/> The incumbent Thomas Drake (1745\u20131819) had died in September.<ref>{{acad|id=DRK764T|name=Drake, Thomas}}</ref> Other candidates for this wealthy living were [[Thomas Dunham Whittaker]], and [[George D'Oyly]] who had better prospects elsewhere at [[Lambeth]]. Hay was successful with the backing of the Manchester municipal establishment. He was seriously ill in 1824.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry H. (Henry Hoyle) |title=The Vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |pages=295-296 |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n106/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\nHay died on 10 December 1839, at Ackworth rectory. His obituary in the ''[[Gentleman's Magazine]]'' compared Hay's role at Peterloo with that of [[Thomas Phillips (mayor)|Sir Thomas Phillips]] in the recent [[Newport Rising]].<ref name=\"GM\"/>\n\n==Family==\nHay married in 1793 Mary Wagstaffe, widow of [[John Astley (painter)|John Astley]], daughter of William Wagstaffe.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lodge |first1=Edmund |title=The Peerage of the British Empire, as at Present Existing, Arranged and Printed from the Personal Communications of the Nobility |date=1832 |publisher=Saunders and Otley |page=237 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=IIsUAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA237 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hay, William Robert}}\n[[Category:1761 births]]\n[[Category:1839 deaths]]\n[[Category:British Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:British barristers]]\n[[Category:Magistrates]]\n", "name_user": "Charles Matthews", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLater life:fx ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Robert_Hay"}
