 1921\u20131925\n| \u2013\n|-\n| NSU 5/15 PS\n| 4-Cylinder\n| 1231\n| 21\n| 2100\n| 1921\u20131925\n| \u2013\n|-\n| NSU 8/32 PS Lieferwagen (Delivery truck)\n| 4-Cylinder\n| 2088\n| 32\n| 2200\n| 1925\u20131927\n| \u2013\n|-\n| NSU 5/25 PS\n| 4-Cylinder\n| 1307\n| 25\n| 2900\n| 1925\u20131928\n| \u2013\n|-\n| NSU 8/40 PS\n| 4-Cylinder\n| 2088\n| 40\n| 2800\n| 1925\u20131927\n| -\n|-\n| NSU 5/15 PS Kompressor|NSU 5/15 PS (Kompressor-Rennwagen) (Supercharger race car)\n| 4-Cylinder\n| 1232\n| 40\u201350\n| 4000\n| 1923\u20131925\n| \u2013\n|-\n| NSU 6/60 PS Kompressor|NSU 6/60 PS (Kompressor-Rennwagen) (Supercharger race car)\n| 6-Cylinder\n| 1482\n| 60\n| 3800\n| 1925\u20131926\n| -\n|-\n| NSU 6/30 PS\n| 6-Cylinder\n| 1567\n| 30\n| 3000\n| 1928\n| -\n|-\n| NSU 7/34 PS\n| 6-Cylinder\n| 1781\n| 34\n| 3200\n| 1928\u20131931\n| -\n|}\n\n=== NSU Car Models Post War ===\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n| image1 = NSU Wankel Spider.jpg| caption1 = NSU Wankel Spider 1964 - 1967\n| width1 = 195\n| image2 = NSU Prinz 4 (Audi Forum Neckarsulm).jpg|caption2 = NSU Prinz 4\n| width2 = 200\n| image3 = CL - Centro storico con auto storiche 18.jpg|caption3 = NSU Sport Prinz \n| width3 = 200\n3\n\n}}\n\nNSU produced the following postwar cars:\n* [[NSU Prinz#NSU Prinz I, II & III|Prinz I, II & III]] I, II, 30 and III (1957\u20131962)\n* [[NSU Prinz#NSU Sport Prinz|Sport Prinz]] (1959\u20131967)\n* [[NSU Prinz#NSU Prinz 4|Prinz 4]], 4L (1961\u20131972)\n* [[NSU Prinz#Prinz 1000, TT|Prinz 1000]], NSU 1000 (1964\u20131972)\n* [[NSU Prinz#Prinz 1000, TT|NSU 1000 TT]], NSU TT, NSU TTS (1965\u20131972)\n* [[NSU Typ 110]] (1965-1967) \n* [[NSU Typ 110#Renaming|NSU 1200]] (1967\u20131972)\n* [[NSU Spider]] (1964\u20131967)\n* [[NSU Ro 80]] (1967\u20131977)\n* NSU K70, produced after VW/Audi takeover as the [[Volkswagen K70]] (1970\u20131975)\n\n===Licence-built models made abroad===\n[[File:NSU P10.jpg|thumb|1970 [[NSU P10]], made by [[Nordex S.A.]] in Uruguay]]\nThe [[NSU Prinz#Related models|NSU Prinz]] was also built in Yugoslavia (by PRETIS), Argentina (by Autoar) and Egypt, under licence.\n\nIn Uruguay, the [[NSU Prinz#NSU Prinz 4|Prinz 4]] was built by Nordex S.A., and a new model, the P6, combined the engine and mechanics of the NSU model with a separate body completely redesigned by Carlos Sotomayor. From 1970, the P10 was built as the successor model to the NSU P6. This had the larger engine of the NSU Prince 1000 and a 21&nbsp;cm extended wheelbase. \n{{clear}}\n\n==NSU motorcycles==\n<gallery>\nFile:Neckarsulm 1,25 HP 1908.jpg|Neckarsulm 1,25 HP 1908\nFile:NSU 3 PS 1911.jpg|NSU 3 PS 1911\nFile:NSU 1913.jpg|NSU 1913\nFile:NSU Fox 1952.jpg|NSU Fox (1952)\nFile:NSU Lux.jpg|NSU Lux (1952)\nFile:ZweiRadMuseumNSU Quickly.JPG|NSU Quickly 50 c.c. T/S MOPED (1953)\nFile:NSU Rennmax Delphinverkleidung.jpg|NSU Rennmax G.P. 250 O.H.C. TWIN (1953)\nFile:ZweiRadMuseumNSU RennFox.JPG|NSU Rennfox G.P. 125 O.H.C. TWIN (1954)\nFile:NSU Rennmax Blauwal.jpg|NSU Rennmax G.P. 250 O.H.C. TWIN (1954)\nFile:NSU Superlux, Bj.1955.jpg|NSU Superlux 250 c.c. T/S SINGLE (1955)\nFile:NSU Sportmax.jpg|NSU Sportmax G.P. 250 O.H.C. SINGLE (1956)\nFile:TriCycle1.jpg|[[Sidecar]] (Germany, 2002)\nFile:NSU 1000.JPG|NSU 1000\nFile:NSU 500.JPG|NSU 500\nFile:NSU 2000.JPG|NSU 2000\nFile:NSU Lambretta.jpg|Prima D\n</gallery>\n\nThe first \"Neckarsulmer Motorrad\" motorcycle was produced in 1901, using a Swiss 1 3/4&nbsp;hp [[Zedel]] single-cylinder AIV (automatic inlet valve) motor with battery/coil ignition, clamped at the underside of a heavy-duty bicycle frame (of NSU manufacture), with the crankcase slightly below and in front of the pedal crank. Specialized racing motorcycles were campaigned from 1905 in events in Europe, the UK, and USA. In 1907, British manager Martin Geiger rode an NSU in the inaugural Isle of Man TT, placing fifth.<ref>{{cite web|last=Williams|first=Greg|title=1954 NSU Max TT: The Odd Man Out|url=http://www.motorcycleclassics.com/classic-german-motorcycles/nsu-max-tt-zmwz13jfzbea.aspx|work=Motorcycle Classics|accessdate=28 March 2013|date=Jan\u2013Feb 2013}}</ref> NSU had several successes in the [[Isle of Man]] [[Isle of Man TT|TT races]] in the 1950s.  In 1908, an NSU v-twin took part in the Ormonde-Daytona beach speed record races for cars and motorcycles, ridden by Eugene Gaestral, who returned with an improved machine the following year.\n\nDuring the 1930s, and in the mid-1950s, NSU was the largest motorcycle producer of the world, in its peak year (1955) producing 350,000 machines.<ref>''Die NSU Story'', Schneider, 1999, Stuttgart, Motorbuch Verlag, {{ISBN|3-613-01853-5}}</ref> NSU holds four world records for speed: 1951, 1953, 1954 and 1955.  In 1956, NSU brought a team of six motorcycles of different engine capacities to Bonneville, Utah, to set World Land Speed Records.  They had success in all categories, and most notably raised the absolute motorcycle speed record to 211&nbsp;mph, with [[Wilhelm Herz]] piloting the Delphin III, a fully streamlined motorcycle with a 500cc supercharged DOHC twin-cylinder Rennsport engine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thevintagent.blogspot.com//2008/09/1956-nsu-breaks-200mph-barrier.html|title=The Vintagent|author=|date=|website=thevintagent.blogspot.com|accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref>  This machine still exists, in the [https://web.archive.org/web/20151007030306/http://www.audi.com/aola/brand/en_lc.html Audi Museum] in [[Stuttgart]], Germany.\n\nThe [[NSU Quickly]] was the most popular [[moped]] of its time.{{Citation needed|date=July 2011}} It was produced between 1953 and 1966 in over 1,000,000 examples and still can be found today all over the world as more than 60% were exported.\n\n==NSU bicycles==\nBicycle production began in 1900 and continued into the early 1960s.<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://oldbike.wordpress.com/1951-nsu-damenrad/\n| title = 1951 NSU Ladies Tourenrad Model 55\n| publisher = Online Vintage Bicycle Museum\n| accessdate = 2011-06-05}}</ref>\n\n==NSU military vehicles==\nNSU was the principal maker of the [[Kettenkrad]] halftracked motorcycle (1940\u20131949)\nThe Sd.Kfz. 2 was designed and built by NSU Motorenwerke AG in Neckarsulm, Germany. Designed and patented in June 1939, it was used for the first time during the invasion of the [[Soviet Union]] [[Operation Barbarossa]] in 1941.\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 101I-725-0184-22, Russland, Soldaten auf Kettenkrad.jpg|right|thumb|220px]]\n\n== Literature ==\n* Peter Schneider: ''NSU-Automobile 1905\u20131977.'' Motorbuch Verlag, Stuttgart 2008, {{ISBN|978-3-613-02867-8}}.\n* Peter Schneider: ''NSU im Bild \u2013 Motorr\u00e4der seit 1900.'' 1. Auflage, Motorbuch Verlag, Stuttgart 2000, {{ISBN|3-613-02063-7}}.\n* Peter Schneider: ''NSU-Motorr\u00e4der, 1900\u20131966, Typenkompass.'' Motorbuch Verlag, Stuttgart 2006, {{ISBN|3-613-02355-5}}.\n* Peter Kirchberg, Thomas Erdmann, Ralph Plagmann: ''Das Rad der Zeit \u2013 Die Geschichte der AUDI AG.'' 3. Auflage, date: 8/00, Hrsg.: AUDI AG Ingolstadt, Verlag Delius Klasing, Bielefeld 2000, {{ISBN|3-7688-1011-9}}.\n* Mareike Hieber, Susanne Jauch, Ralph Plagmann, Gerhard Schwinghammer: ''100 Jahre Automobilbau Neckarsulm.'' Hrsg.: AUDI AG \u2013 Kommunikation Standort Neckarsulm, date: 09/2006.\n* Arthur Westrup: ''Fahre Prinz und Du bist K\u00f6nig. Geschichten aus der NSU-Geschichte.'' Bielefeld: Delius Klasing 1995, {{ISBN|3-7688-0890-4}}.\n\n==See also==\n{{commons|NSU Motorenwerke}}\n* [[List of German companies]]\n* [[List of German cars]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [[:de:Deutsches Zweirad- und NSU-Museum]] [http://www.zweirad-museum.de]\n* [http://www.nsuprinz.com NSU Prinz in German & English]\n* [http://www.vignale-gamine.com/apps/forums/topics/show/2519562-keren-sahar-classic-car-museum-and-a-new-nsu-sport-prinz?next= Restored NSU Sport Prinz in Israel]\n* {{PM20|FID=co/044061|TEXT=Documents and clippings about|NAME=}}\n\n{{Major German motorcycle manufacturers}}\n{{German bicycle manufacturers}}\n{{Volkswagen Group brands}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nsu Motorenwerke Ag}}\n[[Category:NSU Motorenwerke| ]]\n[[Category:Motorcycle manufacturers of Germany]]\n[[Category:Defunct motor vehicle manufacturers of Germany]]\n[[Category:Defunct motorcycle manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Cycle manufacturers of Germany]]\n[[Category:Scooter manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Moped manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Vehicle manufacturing companies established in 1873]]\n[[Category:Vehicle manufacturing companies disestablished in 1977]]\n[[Category:1873 establishments in Germany]]\n[[Category:1977 disestablishments in Germany]]\n[[Category:Audi]]\n[[Category:Volkswagen Group]]\n[[Category:Car manufacturers of Germany]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Neckarsulm]]\n", "name_user": "Tartanperil", "label": "safe", "comment": "Prima dashboard image added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSU_Motorenwerke"}
{"title_page": "York Museums Trust", "text_new": "{{short description|Charity operating museums and galleries in the City of York, North Yorkshire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox organization\n| name            = York Museums Trust\n| image           = File:Yorkshire Museum.jpg\n| caption         = The Yorkshire Museum, one of the trust's sites.\n| type            = Charity\n| tax_id          =\n| registration_id = 1092466\n| founded_date    = {{Start date|2002|02|26|df=y}}\n| founder         = R I L Guthrie, M J Allen, D E Rayner, R E Rushforth\n| dissolved       = N/A\n| location        = [[York]], England\n| coordinates     = <!-- {{Coord|53.962153|-1.089498|display=inline,title}} -->\n| origins         = Created by City of York Council to manage the city's museums and galleries\n| key_people      = Chairman Sir [[John Lawton (biologist)|John Lawton]] <br> Chief Executive [[Reyahn King]]\n| area_served     = [[Yorkshire]]\n| products        =\n| services        = Operating York's city-owned museums and galleries\n| focus           = \n| mission         = \"Our Mission is to cherish the collections, buildings and gardens entrusted to us, presenting and interpreting them as a stimulus for learning, a provocation to curiosity and a source of inspiration and enjoyment for all.\"\n| method          = \n| revenue         =\n| disbursed       =\n| expenses        =\n| endowment       =\n| num_volunteers  =352 (2016)<ref name='2016Rep'>{{cite report |url=https://www.yorkmuseumstrust.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/YMGT-Report-and-Financial-Statements-YE-31.03.2016.compressed.pdf |title=Trustees Reports and Financial Statements, Year Ended 31 March 2016 |date=2016 |publisher=York Museums Trust |accessdate=15 February 2018}}</ref>\n| num_employees   =\n| num_members     =\n| affiliations    =\n| subsid          =\n| owner           =\n| motto           =\n| formerly        =\n| website         = {{URL|http://www.yorkmuseumstrust.org.uk|yorkmuseumstrust.org.uk}}\n| footnotes       =\n}}\n\n'''York Museums Trust''' (YMT) is the charity responsible for operating some key museums and galleries in [[York]], England. The trust was founded in 2002 to run York's museums on behalf of the [[York#Governance|City of York Council]].<ref name=HistoryPage>{{cite web|title=History |url=http://www.yorkmuseumstrust.org.uk/Page/AboutHistory.aspx |work=York Museums Trust website |publisher=York Museums Trust |accessdate=14 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121201063851/http://www.yorkmuseumstrust.org.uk/Page/AboutHistory.aspx |archivedate=1 December 2012 }}</ref><ref name=YorkPress>{{cite news|title=Brave new world for museums in York |url=http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/archive/2002/08/01/7922839.Brave_new_world_for_museums_in_York/ |accessdate=15 October 2013 |newspaper=The York Press |date=1 August 2002 }}</ref> It has seen an increase in annual footfall of 254,000 to the venues since its foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.york.gov.uk/info/200645/co-operative_council/797/co-operative_council/3 |title=York Museums Trust |publisher=City of York Council |accessdate=24 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130918074306/http://www.york.gov.uk/info/200645/co-operative_council/797/co-operative_council/3 |archivedate=18 September 2013 }}</ref> In both 2016 and 2017 it saw its annual visitors numbers reach 500,000 people.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.yorkmuseumstrust.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/York-Museums-Trust-Annual-Report-31-March-2018.pdf |title=Trustees Reports and Financial Statements, Year Ended 31 March 2018 |date=2018 |publisher=York Museums Trust |accessdate=31 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Sites==\nThe trust runs four cultural venues and a garden.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:The Yorkshire Museum, York - geograph.org.uk - 885952.jpg|The Yorkshire Museum\nFile:York Museum Gardens.jpg|York Museum Gardens\nFile:Castle Museum York.JPG|The Castle Museum\nFile:York City Art Gallery.JPG|York City Art Gallery\nFile:Spire of St Mary, York.JPG|St Mary's (contemporary art space)\n</gallery>\n\n===The Yorkshire Museum===\n\n{{main|Yorkshire Museum}}\n\nThis is the historic county museum displaying collections inherited from the [[Yorkshire Philosophical Society]] and acting as a regional collecting museum.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://artuk.org/visit/venues/yorkshire-museum-3652 |work= [[Art UK]] | title= Galleries: Yorkshire Museum  | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===York Museum Gardens===\n{{main|York Museum Gardens}}\n\nThe Museum Gardens are a botanical garden containing the [[Yorkshire Museum]] and [[St Mary's Abbey, York|St Mary's Abbey]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.plantnetwork.org/directory/yrk.htm |title=York Museum Gardens |work= PlantNetwork: The Plant Collections Network of Britain and Ireland (2005) | publisher= plantnetwork.org | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===York Castle Museum===\n{{main|York Castle Museum}}\n\nThe Castle Museum is a social history museum housed in two former prison buildings.<ref>{{cite news| url = https://artuk.org/visit/venues/york-castle-museum-3651 |work= [[Art UK]] |title= Galleries: York Castle Museum  | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===York Art Gallery===\n{{main|York Art Gallery}}\n\nYork's Art Gallery has a large collection of paintings and an internationally important collection of studio ceramics.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-14976861|title=Anthony Shaw ceramics collection loaned to York Art Gallery|date=19 September 2011|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|accessdate=24 October 2013}}</ref> In 2012 the trust obtained \u00a37 million of funding for major refurbishment of the gallery.<ref name=\"BBC Redevelopment\">{{cite news|title=York Art Gallery \u00a38m refurbishment to begin in new year|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-20851073|accessdate=28 October 2013|newspaper=BBC News|date=27 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===York St Mary's===\n{{main|St Mary's Church, Castlegate, York}}\n\nYork St Mary's is a contemporary art space in the deconsecrated church of [[St Mary's Church, Castlegate, York|St Mary's, Castlegate]].<ref name=StMarysArt>{{cite web|title=Welcome to York St Marys |url=http://www.yorkstmarys.org.uk/Page/yorkstmarys.aspx |publisher=York Museums Trust |accessdate=15 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017100232/http://www.yorkstmarys.org.uk/Page/YorkStMarys.aspx |archivedate=17 October 2013 }}</ref>\nThe first use of the space was a joint exhibition by a number of artists, but since 2005 St Mary's has hosted installations by individuals, which are changed on a regular basis. The first of these commissions, inspired by the medieval building itself, was a textile work by Caroline Broadhead called ''Breathing Spaces''. This was followed by ''Echo'', a work by Susie MacMurray.\nIn 2012, Laura Belem created ''The Temple of a Thousand Bells'', which used individually-made clear glass bells in a composition combining bell chimes with a narrative describing how a temple sinks into the sea, silencing the music of a thousand bells.<ref>{{cite web| url =http://www.jorvik.co.uk/st-marys-castlegate/ |work= Jorvik an illustrated guide to York |  title=   St Mary\u2019s Church, Castlegate |publisher= jorvik.co.uk | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yourlocallink.co.uk/events/arts-culture/2012/05/installation-the-temple-of-a-thousand-bells.aspx |work=Events Arts & Culture |title=Installation: The Temple of a Thousand Bells |publisher=yourlocallink.co.uk |accessdate=28 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121031102707/http://www.yourlocallink.co.uk/events/arts-culture/2012/05/installation-the-temple-of-a-thousand-bells.aspx |archivedate=31 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Funding==\nThe Trust is primarily funded through the City of York Council and the Arts Council. The Trust also derives substantial revenue from admission charges and other income sources. Total funding and income for 2013/14 is expected to be \u00a35.85 Million.<ref name=fplan>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.yorkcastlemuseum.org.uk/assets/aboutus/ymt%20forward%20plan%202012-18.pdf \n |pages=4 \n |work=York Museums Trust \n |title=Forward Plan 2012 - 2018 \n |publisher=yorkcastlemuseum.org.uk \n |accessdate=28 October 2013 \n }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artscouncil.org.uk/funding/browse-regularly-funded-organisations/npo/york-museums-trust/ |work=National portfolio organisations |title=York Museums Trust |publisher=Arts Council England |accessdate=28 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131010194919/http://www.artscouncil.org.uk/funding/browse-regularly-funded-organisations/npo/york-museums-trust/ |archivedate=10 October 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\n[[File:Middleham Jewel, obverse - hi-res YORYM 1991 43.jpg|thumb|<center>Middleham Jewel</center>]]\n\nOver 1000 nationally important paintings held by the Trust have been made available online as part of a cooperative project with the [[BBC]] and the [[Public Catalogue Foundation]].<ref>{{cite news| url = https://artuk.org/search/search/search/keyword:york-museums-trust |work= [[Art UK]] |title= Galleries: York Museums Trust  | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url =https://artuk.org/search/search/search/keyword:york-museums-trust  |work= [[Art UK]] |title= More about York Museums Trust  | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\nA number of objects with a Yorkshire connection and held by the Trust were included in the BBC History of the World project, including the [[Middleham Jewel]], the [[York helmet]], and a tin of [[Rowntree's]] cocoa from [[Ernest Shackleton]]\u2019s unsuccessful [[Nimrod expedition]] to the [[South Pole]].<ref>{{cite news| url =https://www.bbc.co.uk/ahistoryoftheworld/objects/J8DM8oZzS1iFXV3UaVAusA|work= A History of the World | title= Middleham Jewel  |publisher=BBC | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url =https://www.bbc.co.uk/ahistoryoftheworld/objects/J8DM8oZzS1iFXV3UaVAusA |work= A History of the World | title= York Helmet  |publisher=BBC | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/ahistoryoftheworld/objects/FPpsDoamQd24kvF7Hj0Axw |work= A History of the World | title= Shackleton's tin of Rowntree's Cocoa |publisher=BBC | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n* In 2009 jointly acquired with the [[British Museum]] the [[Vale of York Hoard]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/8254865.stm|title=Getting the most out of treasure|date=17 September 2009|work=BBC news|accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref> a Viking treasure hoard valued at over \u00a31,000,000.<ref>In 2007 the Whelans had been quoted as saying that a conservative estimate for the value of the hoard was about [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]750,000.({{cite web | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/north_yorkshire/6906107.stm |title=Viking treasure hoard uncovered | work=BBC | date=19 July 2007 | accessdate=28 October 2013}})</ref>\n*An exhibition in 2011 of [[David Hockney]]\u2019s largest landscape painting ''[[Bigger Trees Near Warter]]'' was the most well attended since the Trust had taken over the York Art gallery in 2002.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/york/hi/people_and_places/arts_and_culture/newsid_9403000/9403395.stm  |work= York - Arts and Culture | title= Hockney's largest painting pulls the crowds in York  |publisher=BBC | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n*In 2012 the Trust successfully raised enough money to retain one of a pair of Iron Age gold [[torc]]s that had been found in [[Towton]], [[North Yorkshire]].<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-16831708|work= BBC News York | title= Iron Age gold bracelet to stay at Yorkshire Museum  |publisher=BBC | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n*In 2013 the Trust in conjunction with the BBC organised a ''[[Stargazing Live]]'' event at the York Observatory in the York museum gardens.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.york.ac.uk/news-and-events/features/stargazing-live-2013/ |work= BBC Stargazing Live 2013 |authorlink=University of York | title= University helps local community reach for the stars |publisher= york.ac.uk | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n*In 2014 an exhibition at York Castle Museum focussed on the changes brought about by the First World War, in the centenary year of the start of the conflict.<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-23231831|work= BBC News York | title= York Castle Museum lottery grant funds WWI exhibition |publisher=BBC | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n*On 18 March 2020 the Trust announced that it was closing all of its sites because of government advice regarding the ongoing [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.minsterfm.com/news/local/3063896/coronavirus---wednesday-18-march-local-updates/ |title=CORONAVIRUS - Wednesday 18 March local updates |publisher=[[Minster FM]] |date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.yorkstmarys.org.uk York Museums Trust] - official site\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Organisations based in York]]\n[[Category:Museum organizations]]\n[[Category:York Museums Trust| ]]\n[[Category:Musical instrument museums in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Charity operating museums and galleries in the City of York, North Yorkshire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox non-profit\n| name            = York Museums Trust\n| image           = File:Yorkshire Museum.jpg\n| caption         = The Yorkshire Museum, one of the trust's sites.\n| type            = Charity\n| tax_id          =\n| registration_id = 1092466\n| founded_date    = {{Start date|2002|02|26|df=y}}\n| founder         = R I L Guthrie, M J Allen, D E Rayner, R E Rushforth\n| dissolved       = N/A\n| location        = [[York]], England\n| coordinates     = <!-- {{Coord|53.962153|-1.089498|display=inline,title}} -->\n| origins         = Created by City of York Council to manage the city's museums and galleries\n| key_people      = Chairman Sir [[John Lawton (biologist)|John Lawton]] <br> Chief Executive [[Reyahn King]]\n| area_served     = [[Yorkshire]]\n| products        =\n| services        = Operating York's city-owned museums and galleries\n| focus           = \n| mission         = \"Our Mission is to cherish the collections, buildings and gardens entrusted to us, presenting and interpreting them as a stimulus for learning, a provocation to curiosity and a source of inspiration and enjoyment for all.\"\n| method          = \n| revenue         =\n| disbursed       =\n| expenses        =\n| endowment       =\n| num_volunteers  =352 (2016)<ref name='2016Rep'>{{cite report |url=https://www.yorkmuseumstrust.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/YMGT-Report-and-Financial-Statements-YE-31.03.2016.compressed.pdf |title=Trustees Reports and Financial Statements, Year Ended 31 March 2016 |date=2016 |publisher=York Museums Trust |accessdate=15 February 2018}}</ref>\n| num_employees   =\n| num_members     =\n| affiliations    =\n| subsid          =\n| owner           =\n| motto           =\n| formerly        =\n| website         = {{URL|http://www.yorkmuseumstrust.org.uk|yorkmuseumstrust.org.uk}}\n| footnotes       =\n}}\n\n'''York Museums Trust''' (YMT) is the charity responsible for operating some key museums and galleries in [[York]], England. The trust was founded in 2002 to run York's museums on behalf of the [[York#Governance|City of York Council]].<ref name=HistoryPage>{{cite web|title=History |url=http://www.yorkmuseumstrust.org.uk/Page/AboutHistory.aspx |work=York Museums Trust website |publisher=York Museums Trust |accessdate=14 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121201063851/http://www.yorkmuseumstrust.org.uk/Page/AboutHistory.aspx |archivedate=1 December 2012 }}</ref><ref name=YorkPress>{{cite news|title=Brave new world for museums in York |url=http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/archive/2002/08/01/7922839.Brave_new_world_for_museums_in_York/ |accessdate=15 October 2013 |newspaper=The York Press |date=1 August 2002 }}</ref> It has seen an increase in annual footfall of 254,000 to the venues since its foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.york.gov.uk/info/200645/co-operative_council/797/co-operative_council/3 |title=York Museums Trust |publisher=City of York Council |accessdate=24 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130918074306/http://www.york.gov.uk/info/200645/co-operative_council/797/co-operative_council/3 |archivedate=18 September 2013 }}</ref> In both 2016 and 2017 it saw its annual visitors numbers reach 500,000 people.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.yorkmuseumstrust.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/York-Museums-Trust-Annual-Report-31-March-2018.pdf |title=Trustees Reports and Financial Statements, Year Ended 31 March 2018 |date=2018 |publisher=York Museums Trust |accessdate=31 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Sites==\nThe trust runs four cultural venues and a garden.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:The Yorkshire Museum, York - geograph.org.uk - 885952.jpg|The Yorkshire Museum\nFile:York Museum Gardens.jpg|York Museum Gardens\nFile:Castle Museum York.JPG|The Castle Museum\nFile:York City Art Gallery.JPG|York City Art Gallery\nFile:Spire of St Mary, York.JPG|St Mary's (contemporary art space)\n</gallery>\n\n===The Yorkshire Museum===\n\n{{main|Yorkshire Museum}}\n\nThis is the historic county museum displaying collections inherited from the [[Yorkshire Philosophical Society]] and acting as a regional collecting museum.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://artuk.org/visit/venues/yorkshire-museum-3652 |work= [[Art UK]] | title= Galleries: Yorkshire Museum  | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===York Museum Gardens===\n{{main|York Museum Gardens}}\n\nThe Museum Gardens are a botanical garden containing the [[Yorkshire Museum]] and [[St Mary's Abbey, York|St Mary's Abbey]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.plantnetwork.org/directory/yrk.htm |title=York Museum Gardens |work= PlantNetwork: The Plant Collections Network of Britain and Ireland (2005) | publisher= plantnetwork.org | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===York Castle Museum===\n{{main|York Castle Museum}}\n\nThe Castle Museum is a social history museum housed in two former prison buildings.<ref>{{cite news| url = https://artuk.org/visit/venues/york-castle-museum-3651 |work= [[Art UK]] |title= Galleries: York Castle Museum  | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===York Art Gallery===\n{{main|York Art Gallery}}\n\nYork's Art Gallery has a large collection of paintings and an internationally important collection of studio ceramics.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-14976861|title=Anthony Shaw ceramics collection loaned to York Art Gallery|date=19 September 2011|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|accessdate=24 October 2013}}</ref> In 2012 the trust obtained \u00a37 million of funding for major refurbishment of the gallery.<ref name=\"BBC Redevelopment\">{{cite news|title=York Art Gallery \u00a38m refurbishment to begin in new year|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-20851073|accessdate=28 October 2013|newspaper=BBC News|date=27 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===York St Mary's===\n{{main|St Mary's Church, Castlegate, York}}\n\nYork St Mary's is a contemporary art space in the deconsecrated church of [[St Mary's Church, Castlegate, York|St Mary's, Castlegate]].<ref name=StMarysArt>{{cite web|title=Welcome to York St Marys |url=http://www.yorkstmarys.org.uk/Page/yorkstmarys.aspx |publisher=York Museums Trust |accessdate=15 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017100232/http://www.yorkstmarys.org.uk/Page/YorkStMarys.aspx |archivedate=17 October 2013 }}</ref>\nThe first use of the space was a joint exhibition by a number of artists, but since 2005 St Mary's has hosted installations by individuals, which are changed on a regular basis. The first of these commissions, inspired by the medieval building itself, was a textile work by Caroline Broadhead called ''Breathing Spaces''. This was followed by ''Echo'', a work by Susie MacMurray.\nIn 2012, Laura Belem created ''The Temple of a Thousand Bells'', which used individually-made clear glass bells in a composition combining bell chimes with a narrative describing how a temple sinks into the sea, silencing the music of a thousand bells.<ref>{{cite web| url =http://www.jorvik.co.uk/st-marys-castlegate/ |work= Jorvik an illustrated guide to York |  title=   St Mary\u2019s Church, Castlegate |publisher= jorvik.co.uk | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yourlocallink.co.uk/events/arts-culture/2012/05/installation-the-temple-of-a-thousand-bells.aspx |work=Events Arts & Culture |title=Installation: The Temple of a Thousand Bells |publisher=yourlocallink.co.uk |accessdate=28 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121031102707/http://www.yourlocallink.co.uk/events/arts-culture/2012/05/installation-the-temple-of-a-thousand-bells.aspx |archivedate=31 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Funding==\nThe Trust is primarily funded through the City of York Council and the Arts Council. The Trust also derives substantial revenue from admission charges and other income sources. Total funding and income for 2013/14 is expected to be \u00a35.85 Million.<ref name=fplan>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.yorkcastlemuseum.org.uk/assets/aboutus/ymt%20forward%20plan%202012-18.pdf \n |pages=4 \n |work=York Museums Trust \n |title=Forward Plan 2012 - 2018 \n |publisher=yorkcastlemuseum.org.uk \n |accessdate=28 October 2013 \n }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artscouncil.org.uk/funding/browse-regularly-funded-organisations/npo/york-museums-trust/ |work=National portfolio organisations |title=York Museums Trust |publisher=Arts Council England |accessdate=28 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131010194919/http://www.artscouncil.org.uk/funding/browse-regularly-funded-organisations/npo/york-museums-trust/ |archivedate=10 October 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\n[[File:Middleham Jewel, obverse - hi-res YORYM 1991 43.jpg|thumb|<center>Middleham Jewel</center>]]\n\nOver 1000 nationally important paintings held by the Trust have been made available online as part of a cooperative project with the [[BBC]] and the [[Public Catalogue Foundation]].<ref>{{cite news| url = https://artuk.org/search/search/search/keyword:york-museums-trust |work= [[Art UK]] |title= Galleries: York Museums Trust  | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url =https://artuk.org/search/search/search/keyword:york-museums-trust  |work= [[Art UK]] |title= More about York Museums Trust  | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\nA number of objects with a Yorkshire connection and held by the Trust were included in the BBC History of the World project, including the [[Middleham Jewel]], the [[York helmet]], and a tin of [[Rowntree's]] cocoa from [[Ernest Shackleton]]\u2019s unsuccessful [[Nimrod expedition]] to the [[South Pole]].<ref>{{cite news| url =https://www.bbc.co.uk/ahistoryoftheworld/objects/J8DM8oZzS1iFXV3UaVAusA|work= A History of the World | title= Middleham Jewel  |publisher=BBC | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url =https://www.bbc.co.uk/ahistoryoftheworld/objects/J8DM8oZzS1iFXV3UaVAusA |work= A History of the World | title= York Helmet  |publisher=BBC | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/ahistoryoftheworld/objects/FPpsDoamQd24kvF7Hj0Axw |work= A History of the World | title= Shackleton's tin of Rowntree's Cocoa |publisher=BBC | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n* In 2009 jointly acquired with the [[British Museum]] the [[Vale of York Hoard]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/8254865.stm|title=Getting the most out of treasure|date=17 September 2009|work=BBC news|accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref> a Viking treasure hoard valued at over \u00a31,000,000.<ref>In 2007 the Whelans had been quoted as saying that a conservative estimate for the value of the hoard was about [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]750,000.({{cite web | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/north_yorkshire/6906107.stm |title=Viking treasure hoard uncovered | work=BBC | date=19 July 2007 | accessdate=28 October 2013}})</ref>\n*An exhibition in 2011 of [[David Hockney]]\u2019s largest landscape painting ''[[Bigger Trees Near Warter]]'' was the most well attended since the Trust had taken over the York Art gallery in 2002.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/york/hi/people_and_places/arts_and_culture/newsid_9403000/9403395.stm  |work= York - Arts and Culture | title= Hockney's largest painting pulls the crowds in York  |publisher=BBC | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n*In 2012 the Trust successfully raised enough money to retain one of a pair of Iron Age gold [[torc]]s that had been found in [[Towton]], [[North Yorkshire]].<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-16831708|work= BBC News York | title= Iron Age gold bracelet to stay at Yorkshire Museum  |publisher=BBC | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n*In 2013 the Trust in conjunction with the BBC organised a ''[[Stargazing Live]]'' event at the York Observatory in the York museum gardens.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.york.ac.uk/news-and-events/features/stargazing-live-2013/ |work= BBC Stargazing Live 2013 |authorlink=University of York | title= University helps local community reach for the stars |publisher= york.ac.uk | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n*In 2014 an exhibition at York Castle Museum focussed on the changes brought about by the First World War, in the centenary year of the start of the conflict.<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-23231831|work= BBC News York | title= York Castle Museum lottery grant funds WWI exhibition |publisher=BBC | accessdate= 28 October 2013}}</ref>\n*On 18 March 2020 the Trust announced that it was closing all of it's sites because of government advice regarding the ongoing [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.minsterfm.com/news/local/3063896/coronavirus---wednesday-18-march-local-updates/ |title=CORONAVIRUS - Wednesday 18 March local updates |publisher=[[Minster FM]] |date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.yorkstmarys.org.uk York Museums Trust] - official site\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Organisations based in York]]\n[[Category:Museum organizations]]\n[[Category:York Museums Trust| ]]\n[[Category:Musical instrument museums in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Neils51", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling - it's->its", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/York_Museums_Trust"}
{"title_page": "Erotomania", "text_new": "{{about|a delusional disorder|an abnormally strong or persistent sexual desire|hypersexuality}}\n{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name = <!--{{PAGENAME}} by default-->\n| synonym = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| pronounce = \n| specialty = <!-- from Wikidata, can be overwritten -->\n| symptoms =\n| complications =\n| onset =\n| duration =\n| types = \n| causes =\n| risks =\n| diagnosis =\n| differential =\n| prevention =\n| treatment =\n| medication =\n| prognosis =\n| frequency =\n| deaths =\n}}\n'''Erotomania''' is listed in the [[DSM-5]] as a subtype of a [[delusional disorder]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Oliveira |first1=C. |last2=Alves |first2=S. |last3=Ferreira |first3=C. |last4=Agostinho |first4=C. |last5=Avelino |first5=M.J.|date=2016|title=Erotomania-A review of De Clerambault's Syndrome.|url=|journal=The Journal of the European Psychiatric Association|volume=33|pages=664|via=}}</ref> It is a relatively uncommon [[paranoia|paranoid]] condition that is characterized by an individual's delusions of another person being [[infatuation|infatuated]] with them.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Segal, J.H.|date=1989|title=Erotomania revisited: From Kraepelin to DSM-III-R|url=|journal=The American Journal of Psychiatry|volume=146|issue=10|pages=1261\u20131266|doi=10.1176/ajp.146.10.1261|pmid=2675641}}</ref> This disorder is most often seen (though not exclusively) in female patients that are shy, dependent and sexually inexperienced. The object of the delusion is typically a male who is unattainable due to high social or financial status, marriage or disinterest.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last1=Jordan |first1=H.W. |last2=Lockert |first2=E.W. |last3=Johnson-Warren |first3=M. |last4=Cabell |first4=C. |last5=Cooke |first5=T. |last6=Greer |first6=W. |last7=Howe |first7=G.|date=2006|title=Erotomania revisisted: Thirty-four years later|url=|journal=Journal of the National Medical Association|volume=98|pages=787\u2013793|via=}}</ref> The object of obsession may also be imaginary, deceased or someone the patient has never met. [[Delusions of reference]] are common, as the erotomanic individual often perceives that they are being sent messages from the secret admirer through innocuous events such as seeing license plates from specific states.<ref name=\":1\" /> Commonly, the onset of erotomania is sudden, and the course is chronic.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Presentation==\nErotomania is more common in women, but men are more likely to exhibit violent and [[stalker]]-like behaviors.<ref name=\":1\" /> The core symptom of the disorder is that the sufferer holds an unshakable belief that another person is secretly in love with them. In some cases, the sufferer may believe several people at once are \"secret admirers\". Most commonly, the individual has delusions of being loved by an unattainable man who is usually an acquaintance or someone the person has never met. The sufferer may also experience other types of delusions concurrently with erotomania, such as delusions of reference, wherein the perceived admirer secretly communicates their love by subtle methods such as body posture, arrangement of household objects, colors, license plates on cars from specific states, and other seemingly innocuous acts (or, if the person is a public figure, through clues in the media). Some delusions may be extreme such as the conception, birth, and kidnapping of children that never existed. The delusional objects may be replaced by others over time, and some may be chronic in fixed forms.<ref name=\":1\" /> Denial is characteristic with this disorder as the patients do not accept the fact that their object of delusion may be married, unavailable, or uninterested. The phantom lover may also be imaginary or deceased. Erotomania has two forms: primary and secondary. Primary erotomania is also commonly referred to as de Clerambault's syndrome and Old Maid's Insanity<ref name=\":2\" /> and it exists alone without comorbidities, has a sudden onset and a chronic outcome.<ref name=\":1\" /> The secondary form is found along with mental disorders like paranoid schizophrenia, often includes [[persecutory delusions]], [[hallucination]]s, and grandiose ideas, and has a more gradual onset.<ref name=\":1\" /> Patients with a \"fixed\" condition are more seriously ill with constant delusions and are less responsive to treatment. These individuals are usually timid, dependent women that are often sexually inexperienced.<ref name=\":1\" /> In those with a more mild, recurrent condition, delusions are shorter-lived and the disorder can exist undetected by others for years.<ref name=\":2\" /> Problematic behaviors include actions like calling, sending letters and gifts, making unannounced house visits and other persistent stalking behaviors.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Cause==\nErotomania may present as a primary mental disorder, or as a symptom of another psychiatric illness. With secondary erotomania, the erotomanic delusions are due to other mental disorders such as bipolar I disorder or schizophrenia. Symptoms may also be precipitated by alcoholism and the use of antidepressants.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Seeman, M.V.|date=2016|title=Erotomania and recommendations for treatment|url=|journal=Psychiatric Quarterly|volume=87|issue=2|pages=355\u2013364|doi=10.1007/s11126-015-9392-0}}</ref> There may be a potential genetic component involved as family histories of first degree relatives with histories of psychiatric disorders are common. [[Sigmund Freud]] explained erotomania as a defense mechanism to ward off homosexual impulses which can lead to strong feelings of paranoia, denial, displacement and projection. Similarly, it has been explained as a way to cope with severe loneliness or ego deficit following a major loss.<ref name=\":1\" /> Erotomania may also be linked to unsatiated urges dealing with homosexuality or narcissism.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Kelly, B.D.|date=2005|title=Erotomania: Epidemiology and management|url=|journal=CNS Drugs|volume=19|pages=657\u2013669|doi=10.2165/00023210-200519080-00002}}</ref> Some research shows brain abnormalities occurring in patients with erotomania such as heightened temporal lobe asymmetry and greater volumes of lateral ventricles than those with no mental disorders.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Treatment==\nPrognosis differs from person to person, and the ideal treatment is not completely understood. Treatment for this disorder gains the best results when tailored specifically for each individual. To date, the mainline pharmacological treatments have been pimozide (a typical antipsychotic which was also approved for treating Tourette's Syndrome),<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> and atypical anti-psychotics like risperidone and clozapine.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> Non-pharmacologic treatments that have shown some degree of efficacy are electroconvulsive therapy (ECT), supportive psychotherapy, family and environment therapy,<ref name=\":1\" /> rehousing, risk management and treating underlying disorders in cases of secondary erotomania.<ref name=\":2\" /> ECT may provide temporary remission of delusional beliefs; anti-psychotics help attenuate delusions and reduce agitation or associated dangerous behaviors, and SSRIs may be used to treat secondary depression.<ref name=\":1\" /> In delusional disorder there is some evidence that pimozide has superior efficacy compared with other antipsychotics. Psychosocial psychiatric interventions can enhance the quality of life through allowing some social functioning, and treating comorbid disorders is a priority for secondary erotomania.<ref name=\":2\" /> Family therapy, adjustment of socio-environmental factors, and replacing delusions with something positive may be beneficial to all. In most cases, harsh confrontation should be avoided.<ref name=\":1\" /> Structured risk assessment helps to manage risky behaviors in those individuals more likely to engage in actions that include violence, stalking, and crime.<ref name=\":2\" /> For particularly troublesome cases, neuroleptics and enforced separation may be moderately effective.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==History==\n[[File:Female patient suffering from erotomania, 1843 Wellcome L0022720.jpg|thumb|268x268px|M.S.P. \"Female patient suffering from erotomania,\" from [[Alexander Morison]]'s ''The Physiognomy of Mental Diseases'']]Early references to the condition can be found in the work of [[Hippocrates]], Freud (1911), G.G. de Cl\u00e9rambault (1942),<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Erasistratus]], [[Plutarch]] and [[Galen]]. Parisian physician, Bartholomy Pardoux (1545-1611) covered the topics of nymphomania and erotomania.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 1623, erotomania was referred to in a treatise by Jacques Ferrand<ref name=\":1\" /> (Maladie d'amour ou M\u00e9lancolie \u00e9rotique) and has been called \"erotic paranoia\" and \"erotic self-referent delusion\" until the common usage of the terms erotomania and de Cl\u00e9rambault's syndrome. In 1971 and 1977, M.V. Seeman referred to the disorder as \"phantom lover syndrome\" and \"psychotic erotic transference reaction and delusional loving\".<ref name=\":1\" /> Emil Kraepelin and Bernard also wrote of erotomania and more recently, Winokur, Kendler, and Munro have contributed to knowledge on the disorder.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nG. E. Berrios and N. Kennedy outlined in 'Erotomania: a conceptual history' (2002)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Berrios GE, Kennedy N|date=2002|title=Erotomania: a conceptual history|url=|journal=History of Psychiatry|volume=13 (52, pt4)|pages=381\u2013400|via=}}</ref> several periods of history through which the definition of erotomania has changed considerably:\n*Classical times \u2013 early eighteenth century: General disease caused by unrequited love\n*Early eighteenth-beginning of nineteenth century: Practice of excess physical love (akin to [[nymphomania]] or [[satyriasis]])\n*Early nineteenth century \u2013 beginning twentieth century: Unrequited love as a form of mental disease\n*Early twentieth century \u2013 present: Delusional belief of \"being loved by someone else\"\n\nIn one case, erotomania was reported in a patient who had undergone surgery for a ruptured [[cerebral aneurysm]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Anderson |first1=CA |last2=Camp |first2=J |last3=Filley |first3=C.M.|date=1998|title=Erotomania after aneurysmal subarachnoid hemorrhage: case report and literature review|url=|journal=J Neuropsychiatry Clin Neurosci|volume=10|issue=3 |pages=330\u2013337|doi=10.1176/jnp.10.3.330 |pmid=9706541 }}</ref>\n\n==Well-known cases==\nIn his paper that described the syndrome, de Cl\u00e9rambault referenced a patient he had counselled who was obsessed with British monarch [[George V]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://crimefeed.com/2013/10/9-stalkers-that-make-us-glad-were-not-famous/|title=9 Stalkers That Make Us Glad We're Not Famous.|last1=McDonnell |last2=Margaux |last3=McPadden.|date=2013}}</ref> She had stood outside [[Buckingham Palace]] for hours at a time, believing that the king was communicating his desire for her by moving the curtains.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nParallels were drawn between this and a 2011 case where the body of a homeless American man was found on a secluded island in St. James Park, within sight of Buckingham Palace. The man had sent hundreds of \"strange and offensive\" packages to [[Queen Elizabeth II]] over the previous 15 years.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe assassination attempt on [[Ronald Reagan]] by [[John Hinckley, Jr.]] has been reported to have been driven by an erotomanic fixation on [[Jodie Foster]], whom Hinckley was attempting to impress.\n\nLate night TV entertainer [[David Letterman]] and former astronaut [[Story Musgrave]] were both stalked by [[Margaret Mary Ray]], who suffered from erotomania.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nMichael David Barrett allegedly suffered from erotomania, stalking ESPN correspondent [[Erin Andrews]] across the country, trying to see her and taking lewd videos.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIt is important to note that many cases of obsession or stalking can be linked to erotomania but do not always necessarily go hand in hand.\n\n==Culture and society==\n{{Unreliable sources|section|reason=psychoanalysis|date=February 2020}}\n\nDepictions of erotomania can be seen in these films:<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Gediman|first=Helen|date=2016|title=Stalker, Hacker, Voyeur, Spy: A Psychoanalytic Study of Erotomania, Voyeurism, Surveillance, and Invasions of Privacy|url=|journal=Karnac Books.|volume=|pages=21\u201334|via=}}</ref>\n*''[[Play Misty for Me]]''\n*''[[The Story of Ad\u00e8le H.]]''\n*''[[Ingrid Goes West]]''\n*''[[Wicker Park (film)|Wicker Park]]''\n*''[[The Crush (1993 film)|The Crush]]''\n*''[[Fatal Attraction]]''\n*''[[Indiscretion (film)|Indiscretion]]''\n*''[[Enduring Love]]'' (Ian McEwan novel)\n*''[[He Loves Me... He Loves Me Not (film)|He Loves Me... He Loves Me Not]]''\n*''[[Joker (2019 film)|Joker]]''\n\nErotomania is also in:\n*''[[Coronation Street]]'': 1992/1993 - Carmel Finnan, an Irish Nanny looking after Gail Platt's kids, believing she is in love with Martin Platt and is also sure that he loves her.\n*''[[Criminal Minds]]'': season 1 episode 5 (\"Broken Mirror\"); episode 18 (\"Somebody's Watching\"); and season 8 episode 9 (\"Magnificent Light\")\n*''[[Chance (TV series)|Chance]]'': season 1 episode 3 (\"Hiring It Done\")\n*''[[Law & Order]]'', season 3 episode 18 (\"Animal Instinct\")\n*''[[Orange Is the New Black]]'': season 2 episode 4 (\"A Whole Other Hole\")\n\nVoice : Season 1 Episode 10: a person suffering from the disorder attacks a police since he believes she's getting in the way of his lover.\n\n==See also==\n{{Columns-list|\n* [[Ga\u00ebtan Gatian de Cl\u00e9rambault]]\n* [[Ad\u00e8le Hugo]]\n* [[Case of Aim\u00e9e]]\n* [[Delusion]]\n* [[Delusional disorder]]\n* [[Erotolepsy]]\n